In Linux, there are various commands for managing users and groups. Here are the most commonly used commands:

User Management Commands
Create a new user:

bash
Copy code
sudo adduser username
or

bash
Copy code
sudo useradd username
Delete a user:

bash
Copy code
sudo deluser username
or

bash
Copy code
sudo userdel username
Modify a user:

bash
Copy code
sudo usermod options username
Change a user's password:

bash
Copy code
sudo passwd username
Display user information:

bash
Copy code
id username
or

bash
Copy code
getent passwd username
List all users:

bash
Copy code
cat /etc/passwd
Lock a user account:

bash
Copy code
sudo passwd -l username
Unlock a user account:

bash
Copy code
sudo passwd -u username
Group Management Commands
Create a new group:

bash
Copy code
sudo addgroup groupname
or

bash
Copy code
sudo groupadd groupname
Delete a group:

bash
Copy code
sudo delgroup groupname
or

bash
Copy code
sudo groupdel groupname
Modify a group:

bash
Copy code
sudo groupmod options groupname
Add a user to a group:

bash
Copy code
sudo usermod -aG groupname username
Remove a user from a group:

bash
Copy code
sudo gpasswd -d username groupname
List all groups:

bash
Copy code
cat /etc/group
Display group information:

bash
Copy code
getent group groupname
Other Useful Commands
Change user's primary group:

bash
Copy code
sudo usermod -g groupname username
Change user's home directory:

bash
Copy code
sudo usermod -d /new/home/dir username
Create a system user:

bash
Copy code
sudo adduser --system username
Create a system group:


Copy code
sudo addgroup --system groupname
These commands should cover most of the common tasks associated with managing users and groups in a Linux system.






